Looking at the `getBinaryValue` method in `TreeTraversingParser.java`, I can see the issue. When a `TextNode` contains base64-encoded text and `getBinaryValue` is called with a `Base64Variant`, the current implementation doesn't properly decode the base64 string using the provided variant. Let me examine the current implementation:

```java
@Override
public byte[] getBinaryValue(Base64Variant b64variant)
    throws IOException, JsonParseException
{
    // Multiple possibilities...
    JsonNode n = currentNode();
    if (n != null) {
        // [databind#2096]: although `binaryValue()` works for real binary node
        // and embedded "POJO" node, coercion from TextNode may require variant, so:
        byte[] data = n.binaryValue();  // This will return null for TextNode
        if (data != null) {
            return data;
        }
        if (n.isPojo()) {
            Object ob = ((POJONode) n).getPojo();
            if (ob instanceof byte[]) {
                return (byte[]) ob;
            }
        }
    }
    // otherwise return null to mark we have no binary content
    return null;
}
```

The issue is that when the current node is a `TextNode` containing base64-encoded text, the method calls `n.binaryValue()` which returns `null` for text nodes, and doesn't attempt to decode the text using the provided `Base64Variant`.

Let me check what imports are available to see how to properly handle base64 decoding:

